article.description: Katie Smith had 20 of her 23 points in the second half and overtime to lead the Minnesota Lynx to a 58-50 victory Wednesday night over the Houston Comets.
article.headline: Guard scores 20 of her 23 after the half
article.linkText: Smith thrives after halftime to pace Lynx in OT
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Helen Darling is used to being the smallest
player on the court, but she made two big plays when the Minnesota
Lynx needed them most.

Darling hit a jumper to get Minnesota rolling in overtime and
came up with a key offensive rebound as the Lynx shut out Houston
in the extra session for a 58-50 victory Wednesday night.

Darling, a 5-foot-6 guard, got her only basket of the game on an
18-foot jump shot from the corner on the first possession in
overtime. Then, with the Lynx clinging to a 54-50 lead with 40
seconds to play, she fought through a crowd to come up with an
offensive rebound that helped seal the victory.

"We laugh and joke because I can't jump that high, but I was
determined to get the ball and I just kept jumping until I got
it," Darling said.

Katie Smith scored 20 of her 23 points in the second half and
overtime, and followed Darling's rebound by hitting four straight
free throws as Minnesota completed its comeback victory. The Lynx
trailed 47-39 with two minutes to play, then scored 19 of the final
22 points.

"I feel like mud," Houston coach Van Chancellor said.
"There's not been many games in my career like that. We had the
lead. We just couldn't make a play."

Smith forced overtime with a short jumper after a drive along
the baseline with 5.1 seconds left to tie the game at 50. Tiffani
Johnson's 4-foot baseline jumper rimmed out at the buzzer at the
other end of the court for Houston.

"(Johnson) got a wide-open shot, but we wanted to keep the ball
out of the hands of Sheryl Swoopes and Michelle Snow and that's
what we did," Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said.

Smith scored six of Minnesota's eight points in overtime, and
the Comets came up empty on all six possessions as the Lynx pulled
away and snapped a three-game losing streak. Smith connected on
eight of 20 shots three nights after she scored just five points on
1-for-3 shooting against Los Angeles.

"Individually, you want to make things happen, but you want to
do it within the framework of the team," Smith said. "I think
(Houston) guarded me a little differently, we set better picks, I
was being more aggressive. It was a combination of things."

Lucienne Berthieu led Houston with 11 points and Snow grabbed 15
rebounds for the Comets, who shot a season-low 32.3 percent.

The Comets made just one basket in the final seven minutes of
the game, a 10-foot jumper by Swoopes with 17 seconds left that
gave Houston a 49-46 lead. But Minnesota converted on a quick layup
by Nicole Ohlde, and Dominique Canty hit just one of two free
throws to set up Smith's tying basket.

"It shouldn't have gone into overtime," said Swoopes, who
finished with nine points. "We were in a very good position to
pull it out. Things like that shouldn't happen. If you've got an
eight-point lead with two minutes to go, if you play hard and
execute, you should win."
